## 3. WebSocket Management

### 🔴 3.1 — No heartbeat/health check for Binance WS connections *(Critical)*

**Files:** [websocket_manager.py](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#L207-L286)

The [_run_stream_loop](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#207-287) uses `websockets.connect(ping_interval=20, ping_timeout=20)`, which relies on library-level pings. However, there is **no application-level health check**. If the Binance WS silently stops sending data (a known issue — Binance "zombie connections"), the code will hang on `await ws.recv()` indefinitely because no timeout is set.

**Fix:** Add `asyncio.wait_for` with a timeout:
```python
try:
    msg = await asyncio.wait_for(ws.recv(), timeout=30)
except asyncio.TimeoutError:
    logger.warning(f"[{tag}] No data received in 30s, reconnecting...")
    break  # exits inner loop, outer loop reconnects
```

### 🟠 3.2 — Dynamic subscribe/unsubscribe race conditions *(High)*

**Files:** [websocket_manager.py](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#L46-L91)

[connect()](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#40-53) publishes a subscribe command to Redis (`market:cmd_kline_sub`), which is then picked up by [redis_listener()](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#143-204), which sends it to Binance. But: 
- The [id](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/WatchlistSidebar.tsx#17-162) field uses `len(self.subscribed_streams)` — this is not a unique monotonic counter; it can collide
- [_unsubscribe_stream](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#72-92) uses `asyncio.ensure_future` — fire-and-forget with no error propagation
- If the WS reconnects between subscribe and unsubscribe, the stream tracking gets out of sync

**Fix:** Use an `itertools.count()` for unique IDs and await unsubscribe with error handling.

### 🟠 3.3 — `!ticker@arr` subscribes on BOTH spot and futures *(High)*

**Files:** [websocket_manager.py](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/services/websocket_manager.py#L333-L334)

Both spot and futures WebSocket connections subscribe to `!ticker@arr`. This means **every ticker update from every symbol on both exchanges** is received. Binance Spot has ~2,000+ trading pairs; Futures has ~300+. At 1 update/second per symbol, that's easily 2,000+ messages/second being parsed and filtered.

**Fix:** Instead of `!ticker@arr`, subscribe only to individual `<symbol>@ticker` streams for the symbols in the watchlist. This dramatically reduces message volume:
```python
# Instead of !ticker@arr (ALL symbols):
streams = [f"{sym.lower()}@ticker" for sym in self.global_watchlist_syms]
```

### 🟡 3.4 — Frontend reconnect has no exponential backoff *(Medium)*

**Files:** [useMarketData.ts](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/hooks/useMarketData.ts#L108), [WatchlistSidebar.tsx](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/WatchlistSidebar.tsx#L90)

Both frontend WebSocket connections use a fixed 3-second reconnect delay. If the server is down for an extended period, this creates constant reconnect storms.

**Fix:** Use exponential backoff: `Math.min(3000 * 2^attempt, 30000)`.

