## 5. Frontend Data Flow

### 🟠 5.1 — `[...baseData, update]` creates full array copies on every WS message *(High)*

**Files:** [useMarketData.ts](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/hooks/useMarketData.ts#L82-L98)

Every incoming WebSocket message triggers either:
```typescript
const newData = [...baseData];          // shallow copy of 1000+ candles
newData[newData.length - 1] = update;
return newData;
// OR
return [...baseData, update];           // shallow copy + append
```

With Binance sending updates multiple times per second, this creates ~1,000-element array copies at 1–2 Hz, putting pressure on garbage collection.

**Fix:** Use an immutable data structure or accumulate updates in a mutable ref and only flush to state on an animation frame:
```typescript
const pendingUpdateRef = useRef<KlineData | null>(null);

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    pendingUpdateRef.current = JSON.parse(event.data);
};

useEffect(() => {
    const id = requestAnimationFrame(function tick() {
        const update = pendingUpdateRef.current;
        if (update) {
            pendingUpdateRef.current = null;
            setRealtimeData(prev => applyUpdate(prev, update));
        }
        requestAnimationFrame(tick);
    });
    return () => cancelAnimationFrame(id);
}, []);
```

### 🟠 5.2 — Full indicator recalculation on every data update *(High)*

**Files:** [ChartComponent.tsx](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/ChartComponent.tsx#L160-L257)

The indicator `useEffect` (effect #2) depends on `[data, indicators, klineDataForMath]`. Since `data` changes on every WS tick, **all indicators are destroyed and recreated** multiple times per second:

```typescript
// This runs every time a new WS candle update arrives:
Object.values(indicatorSeriesRefs.current).forEach(seriesList => {
    seriesList.forEach(s => { chart.removeSeries(s); });  // expensive DOM removal
});
// Then recalculates SMA, EMA, BOLL, SAR for ALL data points
// Then re-adds all series to the chart
```

This is the single biggest performance bottleneck on the frontend.

**Fix:** 
1. Only update the **last data point** of each indicator series when a WS update arrives (using `series.update()` instead of full `setData()`)
2. Move indicator calculation to `useMemo` and only recalculate when indicators config changes or a new candle is added (not updated)

### 🟡 5.3 — Watchlist polls + WS creates duplicate data fetching *(Medium)*

**Files:** [WatchlistSidebar.tsx](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/WatchlistSidebar.tsx#L28-L56)

The watchlist fetches tickers via HTTP polling every 10 seconds **and** subscribes to a WebSocket for real-time crypto updates. Both write to the same [tickers](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/backend/app/routers/market_data.py#55-78) state with `setTickers(prev => ({ ...prev, ...newData }))`. This means:

- Every 10s, an HTTP response overwrites the WS-provided real-time data with stale REST data
- The WS immediately overwrites it back

**Fix:** Only poll for stock symbols (which don't have WS), and rely solely on WS for crypto:
```typescript
// Only poll stocks
const stocks = stockWatchlist.map(i => i.sym).join(',');
const res = await fetch(`${API_URL}/market/tickers?stock_symbols=${stocks}`);
```

### 🟡 5.4 — [OscillatorPane](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/OscillatorPane.tsx#17-274) linear scan on crosshair move *(Medium)*

**Files:** [OscillatorPane.tsx](file:///home/Sherk/code/ViewingChart/frontend/src/components/OscillatorPane.tsx#L121-L127)

On every crosshair move, the oscillator pane does:
```typescript
seriesRefs.current.forEach((s, i) => {
    const dataVec = s.data();                                    // gets full series data
    const match = dataVec.find((d: any) => d.time === param.time); // O(n) linear scan
});
```

For 1,000+ data points per series × 3 oscillator values × 60Hz crosshair moves, this is up to 180,000 comparisons/second.

**Fix:** Build a `Map<Time, value>` once when data is set, then do O(1) lookups:
```typescript
const dataMap = useMemo(() => {
    const map = new Map();
    seriesData.forEach(d => map.set(d.time, d.value));
    return map;
}, [seriesData]);
```

